@MichaelCropper For learning, you may like this video: [Constructing Visualizations: Marks and Channels](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=48TUmsG_s6U&list=PL9yYRbwpkyks0RzTyTOLPYbHVSRJ68zOO&index=9). This shows basic usage of D3 to plot things on the screen, without any CSV. The rest of that [playlist](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mRNkZ3qHHBw&list=PL9yYRbwpkyks0RzTyTOLPYbHVSRJ68zOO&index=1) provides context for how to use D3 in general.

For example, here's the code that renders some circles, encapsulated as a function:

```js
export const xPosition = (selection, { data, height }) => {
  selection
    .selectAll('circle')
    .data(data)
    .join('circle')
    .attr('cx', (d) => d * 70 + 60)
    .attr('cy', height / 2)
    .attr('r', 30);
};
```
This is what that looks like:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/68416/232969868-e2dbb6af-7a6e-4220-b35d-29b0b8ecc74d.png)

It's not a "bubble chart" or any chart really, but it's a simple precursor to a scatter plot that shows the structure of D3 rendering logic in its basic form. That can be expanded on to, for example, use color like this:

```js
const hue = (selection, { data, height }) => {
  selection
    .selectAll('circle')
    .data(data)
    .join('circle')
    .attr('cx', (d) => d * 70 + 60)
    .attr('cy', height / 2)
    .attr('r', 30)
    .attr('fill', (d, i) => d3.schemeCategory10[i]);
};
```

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/68416/232970261-86b31624-e2fb-439e-a82e-2412c0baba26.png)

The [video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=48TUmsG_s6U&list=PL9yYRbwpkyks0RzTyTOLPYbHVSRJ68zOO&index=9) explains in detail what each part of the code does and how these functions can be invoked. The invocation of this function in the example is somewhat convoluted, but a simple invocation would look like this:

```js
const svg = d3.select('body').append('svg');
xPosition(svg, {
  data: [0, 1, 2, 3, 4],
  height: 150
});
```

